<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="http://talkirish.com/utility/FeedStylesheets/rss.xsl" media="screen"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:slash="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/" xmlns:wfw="http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/"><channel><title>Irish Word a Day - Glas - Green</title><link>http://talkirish.com/blogs/wordaday/archive/2017/05/10/irish-word-a-day-glas-green.aspx</link><description>glas green (Please visit the site to view this media) Example Sentence T&amp;aacute; an f&amp;eacute;ar fada glas. The grass is long and green. (Please visit the site to view this media) Flashcards</description><dc:language>en</dc:language><generator>CommunityServer 2008 SP1 (Build: 30619.63)</generator><item><title>re: Irish Word a Day - Glas - Green</title><link>http://talkirish.com/blogs/wordaday/archive/2017/05/10/irish-word-a-day-glas-green.aspx#8387</link><pubDate>Wed, 19 Jun 2013 12:38:42 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">0644754f-ff87-49dd-b5e3-0e104f790f4a:8387</guid><dc:creator>Scrybler</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;..hhmmm... trying to cement my knowledge here...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The case is nominative and the noun masculine, so I looked it up. The spelling of glas stays the same. It would be the same if the case were dative. Though glais, glaise, glasa are all legitimate declined spellings depending on intended meaning and use.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Had the sentence been vocative or genitive (eg grass of green) then it&amp;#39;s possible it should be spelt glais...so féar glais.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So féar glais would mean grass of green&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;and féar glas would mean green grass&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;On the other hand I might have totally got the wrong end of the stick....&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://talkirish.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=8387" width="1" height="1"&gt;</description></item><item><title>re: Irish Word a Day - Glas - Green</title><link>http://talkirish.com/blogs/wordaday/archive/2017/05/10/irish-word-a-day-glas-green.aspx#8386</link><pubDate>Wed, 19 Jun 2013 12:22:29 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">0644754f-ff87-49dd-b5e3-0e104f790f4a:8386</guid><dc:creator>Scrybler</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;I&amp;#39;m a total beginner but in the phrase as presented, both adjectives are &amp;quot;attributive&amp;quot;... that is they add attributes to the object grass...ie long green. (fada glas)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But in jaicmac&amp;#39;s phrase only long (fada) is attributive. Green (glas) becomes predicative..ie it&amp;#39;s part of the predicate of the sentence. &amp;nbsp;Wouldn&amp;#39;t that require that glas be declined... ie have it&amp;#39;s spelling changed to indicated it&amp;#39;s changed function in the sentence?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dunno really just applying the theory I&amp;#39;ve already learned...&lt;/p&gt;
